05048nam a22007935i 9789814695114DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898146951147 a10.1355/97898146951142doi  a(DE-B1597)522079  a(OCoLC)1100458820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0070002bisacsh1 aKeyes, Charles F, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy Thwarted :bThe Crisis of Political Authority in Thailand /cCharles F Keyes. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (36 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPHIBUNSONGKHRAM AND THE FIRST FAILURE TO ESTABLISH A DEMOCRATIC ORDER -- tSARIT THANARAT AND THE MILITARYMONARCHY ALLIANCE -- tFROM THE OCTOBER 14, 1973 “REVOLUTION” TO THE “PEOPLE’S CONSTITUTION” OF 1997 -- tTHE THAKSIN INTERREGNUM -- tA WELCOME COUP? -- tJUNTA MISSTEPS -- tWHO WILL SPEAK FOR DEMOCRACY? -- tREFERENCE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe coup in Thailand of 22 May 2014, led by General Prayuth Chan-ocha, ended the country's latest attempt to establish a democratic political order. This coup was but the latest intervention by the Thai military dating at least to the 1950s to prevent any true democratic system developing in Thailand. Instead of a democratic order, the military in alliance with the monarchy, the bureaucracy, and many of the most influential business interests have preferred a system of despotic paternalism first introduced in the late 1950s by Field Marshal Sarit Thanarat.Thai society is not, however, the same as it was in the 1950s. Democratic movements have emerged among both the urban middle class and the upcountry cosmopolitan villagers and from the mid-1990s to the early 21st century it seemed as though Thailand was developing a strong democratic system.The rise of the populist Thaksin Shinawatra engendered increasing opposition not only from the urban middle class, whose political party was less successful in elections than Thaksin's party, but especially from military, royalist, bureaucratic and many in the business elite. The 2014 coup was intended to ensure, as a previous coup in 2006 had not succeeded in doing, that the populist challenge to despotic paternalism was ended once and for all. The strong criticisms of the proposed new constitution that would ensure the perpetuation of authoritarian rule may make such rule untenable, but perhaps may also lead to more political turmoil in the kingdom of no longer smiling Thai.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCoups d’état—Thailand—History. 0aDemocracy. 0aDemocracy—Thailand—History. 0aMilitary government—Thailand—History. 0aThailand—History—Coup d’état, 2014. 0aThailand—Politics and government—1988–. 4aPolitical Ideologies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469511440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814695114.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-070099-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BA